 growth in Starlink Subscribers, offset by a 22.9% decline in ARPU due to international expansion and lower-priced plans). Additionally, enterprise and government revenue grew by $126 million, driven by aviation, maritime, and enterprise (+$209 million) and mobile connectivity (+$85 million), partially offset by a $175 million decrease in government connectivity.\n*   **Cost of Revenue:** Increased by $437 million, or 36.0%, primarily due to $276 million in higher depreciation from capitalized launch and satellite costs. Operating expenses also rose by $140 million, driven by ground operating costs (+$50M), customer support/installation (+$42M), payment processor fees (+$19M), freight (+$15M), and warranty costs (+$12M).\n*   **R&D Expenses:** Increased by $82 million, or 66.7%, primarily due to higher costs for next-generation production development of satellites (+$62 million) and Starlink Kits (+$8 million). \n*   **Income from Operations:** Despite rising costs, Connectivity income from operations increased by $155 million (15.0%) to $1,188 million, while Segment Adjusted EBITDA increased by $469 million to $2,087 million.',
