    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided filing chunks, here are the definitions and policies regarding Starlink subscribers and Connectivity revenue:\n\n### **Starlink Subscribers**\n**How They Are Counted:**\n*   A "Starlink Subscriber" is defined as a unique **Service Line** directly assigned to a Starlink.com account registered to a person or entity that does *not* have a direct, negotiated agreement with the Starlink sales team.\n*   A "Service Line" is an individual instance of Starlink broadband internet service provisioned under a subscription plan, generally associated with a specific terminal or group of terminals.\n*   The number of Service Lines is distinct from the number of unique devices, account holders, or physical persons. An individual or business may share a single Service Line among multiple end-users, or conversely, maintain multiple Service Lines (e.g., a Residential line and a Roam line), which would count as two separate subscribers.\n*   The company calculates the total subscriber count as the number of unique Service Lines at the **end of the period**.\n\n**What is Included:**\n*   Both Personal subscription plans (e.g., Residential and Roam) and Business subscription plans (e.g., Local Priority and Global Priority).\n\n**What is Excluded:**\n*   Managed enterprise and government customers with contracts in domains including aviation, maritime, land mobility, fixed sites, and government entities are *not* included in the Starlink Subscriber count.\n\n### **Connectivity Revenue**\n**What is Included:**\nThe Connectivity segment generates revenue from the following primary sources:\n1.  **Consumer Broadband & Mobile Services:** Monthly subscription fees based on geographic market and download speed, as well as variable-priced services based on actual data usage. \n2.  **Starlink Kit and Hardware:** The sale of the Starlink Kit (inclusive of the terminal) and other related hardware. Shipping and handling charges are included in the transaction price but recognized as fulfillment activities, not separate obligations.\n3.  **Enterprise & Government Services:** Revenue from enterprises through contracts structured as a combination of subscriptions, data consumption, and capacity. This also includes revenue from Starlink Mobile service offerings.\n4.  **Government Starshield Contracts:** Long-term, multi-year contracts for the development of a secure satellite network for government and national security applications.\n\n**Revenue Recognition Policies for Connectivity:**\n*   **Services (Broadband & Mobile):** Performance obligations are satisfied *over time* as the customer simultaneously receives and consumes the benefits. Revenue is recognized either ratably over the subscription term or based on actual data usage/consumption. Advanced payments are recorded as deferred revenue on the balance sheet. Consumer broadband contracts are generally month-to-month, while mobile connectivity agreements range from one to five years.\n*   **Hardware (Starlink Kits):** Performance obligations are satisfied at a *point in time* when control transfers to the customer—typically upon delivery, or upon installation for certain enterprise customers. Kit revenue is reported net of sales returns, credits, and chargebacks.\n*   **Starshield (Government Contracts):** For long-term, multi-year contracts, revenue is recognized *over time* using the **cost-to-cost input method**. Revenue is recorded based on costs (materials and labor hours) incurred to date relative to the total estimated cost at completion.',
