    tool_call=ToolCall(
        id='call_86cbc20504d24363904897e4',
        call_id=None,
        name='retrieve_information',
        args='{"prompt":"Find the exact definition and calculation methodology for Starlink ARPU in {{spacex_s1}}. How is ARPU calculated? Is it based on Consumer revenue only or total Connectivity revenue? Is it based on average subscribers during the period or end-of-period subscribers? What is the Q1 2026 ARPU and Q1 2025 ARPU? Also find the exact subscriber count and any details about how the ARPU is computed."}',
        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'Find the exact definition and calculation methodology for Starlink ARPU in {{spacex_s1}}. How is ARPU calculated? Is it based on Consumer revenue only or total Connectivity revenue? Is it based on average subscribers during the period or end-of-period subscribers? What is the Q1 2026 ARPU and Q1 2025 ARPU? Also find the exact subscriber count and any details about how the ARPU is computed.'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Starlink Subscriber ARPU: Definition, Methodology, and Values\n\n## Exact Definition and Calculation Methodology\n\nFrom the S-1 preamble, the calculation is stated verbatim:\n\n> **"We calculate ARPU as service revenue generated from Starlink Subscribers during the period divided by (i) the average number of Starlink Subscribers during the period and by (ii) the number of months in the period."**\n\nExpressed as a formula:\n\n$$\\text{ARPU} = \\frac{\\text{Service revenue from Starlink Subscribers during the period}}{\\text{Average Starlink Subscribers during the period} \\times \\text{Number of months in the period}}$$\n\n---\n\n## Key Methodological Details\n\n### 1. Revenue Basis: Consumer Service Revenue Only — NOT Total Connectivity Revenue\n\nARPU is based on **service revenue generated from Starlink Subscribers** specifically. This is the **consumer subscriber** revenue line, not total Connectivity segment revenue. The MD&A consistently decomposes consumer revenue as:\n\n> "Consumer revenue was composed of 104.7% growth in Starlink Subscribers, offset by a 22.9% decline in Starlink Subscriber ARPU"\n\nEnterprise and government revenue (aviation, maritime, land mobility, fixed sites, government entities) is reported **separately** and is explicitly **excluded** from both the Starlink Subscriber count and the ARPU calculation. The definition of Starlink Subscribers states it:\n\n> "does not include managed enterprise and government customers with contracts in domains including aviation, maritime, land mobility, fixed sites and government entities."\n\nAdditionally, the revenue used is **service revenue** — the Starlink Kit (hardware/terminal) sale revenue is excluded, as the Kit is recognized as a separate performance obligation upon delivery.\n\n### 2. Subscriber Basis: Average During the Period — NOT End-of-Period\n\nThe calculation explicitly uses the **average number of Starlink Subscribers during the period**, not the end-of-period count. This is stated directly in the formula: "divided by (i) the average number of Starlink Subscribers during the period."\n\nNote: While the **ARPU** calculation uses average subscribers, the reported **Starlink Subscribers** metric itself is defined as "the number of unique Service Lines **at the end of the period**."\n\n### 3. Time Normalization: Divided by Number of Months\n\nThe result is normalized to a **per-month** figure by dividing by the number of months in the period (e.g., 3 for a quarter, 12 for a year).\n\n---\n\n## Starlink Subscriber Definition\n\n| Aspect | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Unit of measure** | Unique Service Lines at end of period |\n| **Included** | Personal plans (Residential, Roam) and Business plans (Local Priority, Global Priority) |\n| **Excluded** | Managed enterprise and government customers (aviation, maritime, land mobility, fixed sites, government entities) |\n| **Multiple service lines** | A single customer with both a Residential and a Roam Service Line counts as **two** Starlink Subscribers |\n\n---\n\n## Subscriber Counts\n\n| Period | Starlink Subscribers | YoY Growth |\n|---|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 (three months ended March 31, 2026) | **~10.3 million** | +105% |\n| Q1 2025 (three months ended March 31, 2025) | **~5.0 million** | +91% |\n| FY 2025 (year ended December 31, 2025) | 8.9 million | +99.9% |\n| FY 2024 (year ended December 31, 2024) | 4.4 million | +96.5% |\n| FY 2023 (year ended December 31, 2023) | 2.3 million | — |\n\n---\n\n## ARPU Values\n\n| Period | Starlink Subscriber ARPU | YoY Change |\n|---|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 (three months ended March 31, 2026) | **$66/month** | −22.9% |\n| Q1 2025 (three months ended March 31, 2025) | **$86/month** | — |\n| FY 2025 | $81/month | −11.2% |\n| FY 2024 | $91/month | −8.1% |\n| FY 2023 | $99/month | — |\n\n---\n\n## Strategy and Trend Context\n\nThe company explicitly states a strategy of **prioritizing scale over ARPU**:\n\n> "Our strategy is focused on driving sustainable revenue growth and expanding our margins through operational efficiencies and technological advancements, rather than prioritizing increases in ARPU. This approach aligns with our long-term vision of expanding global connectivity and market access."\n\nThe company expects ARPU to **continue declining**:\n\n> "We generally expect Starlink Subscriber ARPU to continue to decline over the next few years as the portion of our subscriber base outside North America continues to grow, as we add lower priced service plans, and as we adjust the monthly service plan fees we charge for broadband offerings."\n\nThe declines are attributed to:\n- **International expansion** into lower-income markets\n- **Addition of lower-priced service plans**\n- **Adjustments to monthly service plan fees** for broadband offerings\n\nHowever, the company expects these ARPU declines to be **offset by increased scale** and technological advancement in launch, satellite, and user terminal operations, ultimately supporting overall revenue growth and cost reduction.\n\n---\n\n## Illustrative Calculation Check (Q1 2026)\n\nUsing the disclosed figures to sanity-check:\n\n- Q1 2026 Consumer revenue: **$2,148 million** (from the revenue disaggregation table)\n- Q1 2026 ARPU: **$66/month**\n- Months in period: **3**\n- Implied average subscribers: $2,148M ÷ ($66 × 3) ≈ **10.85 million** average subscribers\n\nThis is consistent with a period where subscribers grew from ~5.0M (end of Q1 2025) to ~10.3M (end of Q1 2026), yielding an average in that range. The end-of-period count of 10.3M and the computed average of ~10.85M are in the same ballpark, confirming the methodology.¹\n\n---\n\n¹ *Note: The average subscriber count is not directly disclosed; this is a derived estimate to illustrate the formula. Small discrepancies may arise from rounding in the disclosed ARPU figure or from the exact averaging method used.*',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=45.724,
    error=None,
    success=True
)
