 by average subscribers:\\n\\n- Using Consumer revenue ($2,148M) ÷ end-of-period subscribers (10.3M × 3) = **$69.51/month** — close to but above $66, because (a) end-of-period overstates the average subscriber base, and (b) Consumer revenue includes some hardware (Products) revenue.\\n- Using a simple average of subscribers [(8.9M + 10.3M) ÷ 2 = 9.6M] and Consumer service revenue ex-hardware ($2,148M − $380M = $1,768M): $1,768M ÷ (9.6M × 3) = **$61.39/month** — close to but below $66.\\n\\nThe filing\'s $66/month falls between these bounds, consistent with the disclosed methodology (Consumer service revenue ÷ average subscribers ÷ months). The $105.40 implied by total Connectivity revenue is **not** a comparable ARPU measure because it conflates revenue from non-Subscriber customers (enterprise, government, Starshield, mobile) and hardware sales with the consumer subscriber base.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Bottom Line\\n\\n- **Implied monthly ARPU using total Q1 2026 Connectivity revenue and disclosed end-of-period subscribers: ≈ $105.40 per subscriber per month.**\\n- This figure is **not comparable** to the filing\'s reported $66/month Starlink Subscriber ARPU because it (i) includes Enterprise & Government, Starshield, and Starlink Mobile revenue from customers excluded from the subscriber count, (ii) includes $380M of hardware (Products) revenue excluded from \\"service revenue,\\" and (iii) uses end-of-period rather than average subscribers.\\n- The filing\'s own $66/month ARPU is the apples-to-apples measure and reflects Consumer service revenue only, normalized by average subscribers during the period.\\n\\n---\\n\\n{\\n  \\"sources\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — MD&A, Revenue Disaggregation, Starlink Subscriber and ARPU definitions\\"\\n    }\\n  ]\\n}"}',
