            'final_result': '## Implied Monthly Starlink ARPU Estimate — Q1 2026\n\n### Source Data (from SpaceX S-1, three months ended March 31, 2026)\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|---|---|\n| Total Connectivity segment revenue | $3,257 million |\n| — Consumer revenue | $2,148 million |\n| — Enterprise & Government revenue (incl. Starlink Mobile) | $1,109 million |\n| Connectivity Products revenue (Starlink Kits/hardware) | $380 million (embedded in Connectivity total) |\n| Connectivity Services revenue (ex-hardware) | $2,877 million |\n| Starlink Subscribers (end of period, March 31, 2026) | ~10.3 million |\n| Months in period | 3 |\n| Filing\'s reported Starlink Subscriber ARPU (Q1 2026) | $66/month |\n\n---\n\n### Primary Estimate — Implied Monthly ARPU Using Total Connectivity Revenue\n\n**Formula:** Total Connectivity Revenue ÷ (End-of-Period Subscribers × Months in Period)\n\n**Calculation:**\n- $3,257M ÷ (10.3M × 3) = $3,257M ÷ 30.9M\n- **Implied monthly ARPU ≈ $105.40 per subscriber per month**\n\n---\n\n### Alternative Estimates for Context\n\n| Revenue Basis Used | Calculation | Implied Monthly ARPU |\n|---|---|---|\n| Total Connectivity revenue ($3,257M) | $3,257M ÷ (10.3M × 3) | **$105.40** |\n| Connectivity Services revenue ex-hardware ($2,877M) | $2,877M ÷ (10.3M × 3) | **$93.07** |\n| Consumer revenue only ($2,148M) | $2,148M ÷ (10.3M × 3) | **$69.51** |\n| Filing\'s reported ARPU (Consumer service rev. ÷ avg. subscribers × months) | — | **$66.00** |\n\nThe filing\'s reported $66/month ARPU is materially lower than the $105.40 implied by dividing total Connectivity revenue by end-of-period subscribers. The gap is explained by the definitional mismatches described below.\n\n---\n\n### Assumptions Stated\n\n1. **Revenue basis:** Total Connectivity segment revenue ($3,257M) is used as the numerator, as the question specifies "Connectivity revenue." This includes Consumer, Enterprise & Government, and embedded Products (hardware) revenue.\n2. **Subscriber basis:** End-of-period count of 10.3 million Starlink Subscribers as of March 31, 2026 is used (the only subscriber figure disclosed for the period).\n3. **Time normalization:** Q1 2026 is treated as 3 months; revenue is assumed to be evenly distributed across the quarter.\n4. **Uniform ARPU assumption:** All 10.3 million subscribers are assumed to generate equal revenue — an oversimplification, since the subscriber base spans 164 countries with materially different price plans.\n5. **No adjustment for subscriber growth within the quarter:** Using end-of-period subscribers rather than the period average overstates ARPU when the subscriber base is growing (it grew from 8.9M at year-end 2025 to 10.3M at quarter-end 2026).\n\n---\n\n### What the Filing\'s Subscriber and Revenue Definitions Exclude From This ARPU Estimate\n\n#### Subscriber-Count Exclusions (per the S-1 definition of "Starlink Subscriber")\n\nThe 10.3 million figure counts **unique Service Lines at end of period** and explicitly **excludes**:\n\n1. **Managed enterprise and government customers** — including aviation, maritime, land mobility, fixed sites, and government entities. These customers have direct, negotiated agreements with the Starlink sales team and are not counted as Starlink Subscribers, even though their revenue is included in Connectivity segment revenue.\n2. **Starlink Mobile / satellite-to-mobile texting users** — approximately 7.4 million monthly unique devices across ~30 countries are reported separately and are **not** included in the 10.3M Starlink Subscriber count.\n3. **Average-subscriber normalization** — the filing\'s own ARPU uses the **average** number of subscribers during the period, not the end-of-period count used here. Using end-of-period count overstates ARPU in a growing subscriber base.\n4. **Service Line vs. person/device distinction** — a single customer with both a Residential and a Roam Service Line counts as **two** subscribers (inflating the count), while multiple end-users sharing one Service Line count as **one** subscriber (deflating the count). The count is of Service Lines, not unique persons, accounts, or physical devices.\n\n#### Revenue Exclusions (per the S-1\'s ARPU definition)\n\nThe filing defines ARPU as **"service revenue generated from Starlink Subscribers during the period divided by (i) the average number of Starlink Subscribers during the period and by (ii) the number of months in the period."** This definition **excludes** from the ARPU numerator:\n\n1. **Enterprise & Government revenue ($1,109M)** — revenue from aviation, maritime, land mobility, fixed-site enterprise, and government customers who are **not** counted as Starlink Subscribers. This revenue is included in total Connectivity revenue but is not generated from the 10.3M subscriber base.\n2. **Starlink Mobile service revenue** — included within Enterprise & Government and tied to the 7.4M mobile devices, not the 10.3M Starlink Subscribers.\n3. **Starshield government contract revenue** — long-term, multi-year government contracts recognized over time using the cost-to-cost input method; included in Enterprise & Government but not generated from Starlink Subscribers.\n4. **Products / Starlink Kit hardware revenue ($380M)** — hardware sales are a separate performance obligation recognized at a point in time (delivery/installation) and are **excluded** from "service revenue" in the ARPU calculation. This hardware revenue is embedded within the Connectivity segment total.\n5. **Service revenue from non-Subscriber customers** — any service revenue from customers not meeting the Starlink Subscriber definition is excluded from the ARPU numerator even though it appears in Connectivity segment revenue.\n\n---\n\n### Reconciliation to the Filing\'s Reported $66/Month ARPU\n\nThe filing\'s $66/month ARPU is internally consistent with Consumer service revenue divided by average subscribers:\n\n- Using Consumer revenue ($2,148M) ÷ end-of-period subscribers (10.3M × 3) = **$69.51/month** — close to but above $66, because (a) end-of-period overstates the average subscriber base, and (b) Consumer revenue includes some hardware (Products) revenue.\n- Using a simple average of subscribers [(8.9M + 10.3M) ÷ 2 = 9.6M] and Consumer service revenue ex-hardware ($2,148M − $380M = $1,768M): $1,768M ÷ (9.6M × 3) = **$61.39/month** — close to but below $66.\n\nThe filing\'s $66/month falls between these bounds, consistent with the disclosed methodology (Consumer service revenue ÷ average subscribers ÷ months). The $105.40 implied by total Connectivity revenue is **not** a comparable ARPU measure because it conflates revenue from non-Subscriber customers (enterprise, government, Starshield, mobile) and hardware sales with the consumer subscriber base.\n\n---\n\n### Bottom Line\n\n- **Implied monthly ARPU using total Q1 2026 Connectivity revenue and disclosed end-of-period subscribers: ≈ $105.40 per subscriber per month.**\n- This figure is **not comparable** to the filing\'s reported $66/month Starlink Subscriber ARPU because it (i) includes Enterprise & Government, Starshield, and Starlink Mobile revenue from customers excluded from the subscriber count, (ii) includes $380M of hardware (Products) revenue excluded from "service revenue," and (iii) uses end-of-period rather than average subscribers.\n- The filing\'s own $66/month ARPU is the apples-to-apples measure and reflects Consumer service revenue only, normalized by average subscribers during the period.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — MD&A, Revenue Disaggregation, Starlink Subscriber and ARPU definitions"\n    }\n  ]\n}'
